It's time for the United States
of America to take

00:00:14.680 --> 00:00:18.590
responsibility for the pain and
suffering and torture and

00:00:18.590 --> 00:00:22.090
murder that's going on
throughout Latin America.

00:00:22.090 --> 00:00:23.970
SHANE SMITH: Maybe one of the
reasons that Mitt Romney is so

00:00:23.970 --> 00:00:26.760
concerned with the drug wars
taking place just south of the

00:00:26.760 --> 00:00:30.500
American border is that it
affects him and his family

00:00:30.500 --> 00:00:31.320
personally.

00:00:31.320 --> 00:00:34.010
Hi, I'm Shane Smith and we're
here at the Vice headquarters

00:00:34.010 --> 00:00:35.180
in Williamsburg, Brooklyn.

00:00:35.180 --> 00:00:38.120
Now, Williamsburg is ground
zero for hipsters.

00:00:38.120 --> 00:00:40.900
Which means it's also ground
zero for partying.

00:00:40.900 --> 00:00:44.080
Which means it's ground
zero for cocaine.

00:00:44.080 --> 00:00:46.870
Now, Vice has talked a lot about
cocaine over the years.

00:00:46.870 --> 00:00:50.750
In fact, one of our magazine
covers featured a mirror with

00:00:50.750 --> 00:00:52.360
a big line of coke
chopped up on it.

00:00:52.360 --> 00:00:55.780
But recently, we followed a
story that made us think twice

00:00:55.780 --> 00:00:58.060
about our historical fascination
with coke.

00:00:58.060 --> 00:00:59.800
And it has to do
with Mormons--

00:00:59.800 --> 00:01:02.600
as in Mitt Romney's family-type
Mormons--

00:01:02.600 --> 00:01:07.480
Mexican drug cartels, polygamy,
kidnapping, cocaine,

00:01:07.480 --> 00:01:09.540
and finally, murder.

00:01:09.540 --> 00:01:11.500
Now, it's a freaky,
freaky story.

00:01:11.500 --> 00:01:14.180
And it's taking place just
south of the US border.

00:01:14.180 --> 00:01:16.310
So we went to check it
out firsthand to see

00:01:16.310 --> 00:01:17.560
what's going on.

00:01:22.620 --> 00:01:25.568
We just passed through from El
Paso, in Texas, which is

00:01:25.568 --> 00:01:27.550
actually one of the safest
cities in America, into

00:01:27.550 --> 00:01:29.560
Juarez, Mexico, which is
actually one of the most

00:01:29.560 --> 00:01:31.000
dangerous cities in the world.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:33.060
In fact, it's the most dangerous
city in the world

00:01:33.060 --> 00:01:34.290
for journalists.

00:01:34.290 --> 00:01:36.990
And we're driving with the
camera rolling, which is, in

00:01:36.990 --> 00:01:40.870
retrospect, very
fucking stupid.

00:01:40.870 --> 00:01:43.551
People always ask me what the
most dangerous place I've ever

00:01:43.551 --> 00:01:44.340
been to is.

00:01:44.340 --> 00:01:46.270
And when I say Mexico, they're
a bit flummoxed.

00:01:46.270 --> 00:01:48.330
And they say, Mexico,
I've been to Mexico.

00:01:48.330 --> 00:01:51.300
I've been to Cancun, Joe's
Tequila Foam Party

00:01:51.300 --> 00:01:52.630
and Boom Boom Room.

00:01:52.630 --> 00:01:55.310
But this Mexico, here in Juarez,
is the Mexico run by

00:01:55.310 --> 00:01:56.190
the narco lords.

00:01:56.190 --> 00:01:57.810
They don't care about what
you're shooting.

00:01:57.810 --> 00:01:59.960
They don't walk up and say, hey,
what's that camera for?

00:01:59.960 --> 00:02:02.200
They just see a camera and
go, that can't be good.

00:02:02.200 --> 00:02:03.710
And bam.

00:02:03.710 --> 00:02:06.320
Now, the drug lords that rule
northern Mexico are like most

00:02:06.320 --> 00:02:07.255
mafia around the world.

00:02:07.255 --> 00:02:10.199
They're very wealthy, and
they're insanely ruthless.

00:02:10.199 --> 00:02:12.520
But the thing that sets the
Mexican cartels apart from the

00:02:12.520 --> 00:02:16.205
other mobs is their seemingly
profound love of murder.

00:02:18.870 --> 00:02:21.010
They put other crime syndicates
to shame with the

00:02:21.010 --> 00:02:23.950
sheer scale of their killing,
not to mention the gruesome,

00:02:23.950 --> 00:02:26.810
eye-catching way they present
their murders, with a kind of

00:02:26.810 --> 00:02:28.060
evil inventiveness.

00:02:31.910 --> 00:02:34.660
And it's not just traditional
gang-on-gang violence, either.

00:02:34.660 --> 00:02:37.860
The cartels kill anyone and
everyone in their way.

00:02:37.860 --> 00:02:40.200
Rivals, witnesses, journalists,
politicians, and

00:02:40.200 --> 00:02:42.140
police are all targets.

00:02:42.140 --> 00:02:44.610
And rather than hiding the
bodies like most criminals,

00:02:44.610 --> 00:02:46.730
they actually want
you to see them.

00:02:46.730 --> 00:02:51.040
And they want you to know
exactly who did it.

00:02:51.040 --> 00:02:54.600
In fact, the war on drugs in
Mexico is so violent that its

00:02:54.600 --> 00:02:58.390
body count is almost 10 times
that of American soldiers

00:02:58.390 --> 00:03:02.750
killed in the real wars in
Iraq and Afghanistan.

00:03:02.750 --> 00:03:05.080
And in a country where it's
supposedly illegal to own

00:03:05.080 --> 00:03:08.140
guns, the narcos are armed
to the teeth with

00:03:08.140 --> 00:03:12.350
state-of-the-art weaponry, 90%
of which are smuggled in from

00:03:12.350 --> 00:03:14.660
the United States, which is
something we got to see

00:03:14.660 --> 00:03:18.880
firsthand as soon as we
arrived in Juarez.

